      • isListeningFor

        public boolean isListeningFor(java.lang.Class<? extends DimpleEvent> eventClass,
                     IDimpleEventSource on)
        Description copied from interface: IDimpleEventListener
        Indicate whether listener will handle events with given eventClass type that originate on given source object or its children.

        This is intended to be used by IDimpleEventSource implementations to determine whether to expend resources to raise events. When this method returns false the listener advertises that it will ignore matching events.

        Specified by:
        isListeningFor in interface IDimpleEventListener

      • raiseEvent

        public boolean raiseEvent(DimpleEvent event)
        Notify listener of a new event.

        This method will visit each handler in order listed by the getHandlersFor(java.lang.Class<? extends com.analog.lyric.dimple.events.DimpleEvent>, com.analog.lyric.dimple.events.IDimpleEventSource) method for the event's concrete class and its source attribute and invoke it's handleEvent method. If the event is marked as consumed then no further handlers will be tried.

        Specified by:
        raiseEvent in interface IDimpleEventListener
        Parameters:
        event - a non-null instance of a subclass of DimpleEvent that has not yet been consumed.
        Returns:
        false if event was not already consumed and no handler was found for it.
        Since:
        0.06
        See Also:
        DimpleEvent.consumed(), DimpleEvent.getSource(), IDimpleEventHandler.handleEvent(DimpleEvent)

      • getHandlersFor

        public java.util.List<DimpleEventListener.IHandlerEntry> getHandlersFor(java.lang.Class<? extends DimpleEvent> eventClass,
                                                               IDimpleEventSource eventSource)
        Returns list of handler entries registered to handle the given event.

        The entries are given in the order in which they would be invoked when calling raiseEvent(DimpleEvent) when passed an event with given eventClass and eventSource. This may include more entries than would be invoked by raiseEvent since that method stops processing if the event is consumed by a handler.

        The list is constructed by checking very source in eventSources(IDimpleEventSource) starting with given eventSource in order and adding entries matching given eventClass in topological order from subclass to superclass. The list is terminated if a blocking handler is found.

        Returns:
        newly allocated mutable list
        Since:
        0.06
        See Also:
        IDimpleEventHandler.isBlocker()

      • eventSources

        public EventSourceIterator eventSources(@Nullable
                               IDimpleEventSource source)
        Iterates over sources of event in hierarchical order from child to parent.

        Specifically, this is equivalent to the ordering that would be produced by: 

         void addSources(List<IDimpleEventSource> sources, IDimpleEventSource source)
 {
     source.add(source);
     if (source.getModelEventSource() != source)
     {
         source.add(source.getModelEventSource());
     }
     if (source.getEventParent() != null)
     {
         addSources(source.getEventParent());
     }
 }

        Iterator is not thread-safe. Expected to be used for a single function call.

        Since:
        0.06

      • unblock

        public boolean unblock(java.lang.Class<? extends DimpleEvent> eventClass,
              IDimpleEventSource target)
        Unblocks specified events from percolating past specified source.

        Simply invokes unregister(IDimpleEventHandler, Class, IDimpleEventSource) with DimpleEventBlocker as the handler. Note that the eventClass and target must exactly match that used with previous block(Class, boolean, IDimpleEventSource) call.

        Returns:
        false if no matching blocker was found.
        Since:
        0.06
